00:06:56.270 --> 00:06:58.462
The 1 there is that [HUM]

00:06:58.462 --> 00:06:59.480
top note.

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:00.770
Then we've got the chugs.

00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:02.650
You remember what chugs are?

00:07:02.650 --> 00:07:03.950
Doing square root of 5.

00:07:03.950 --> 00:07:05.370
And again, half-time drums.

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:16.590
PHIL MORIARTY: Leibniz was a
very famous mathematician,

00:07:16.590 --> 00:07:18.355
developed calculus independently
of Newton.

00:07:18.355 --> 00:07:21.340
And he has this wonderful quote,
which is that music is

00:07:21.340 --> 00:07:23.320
the human mind counting
when it doesn't

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:24.230
know that it's counting.

00:07:24.230 --> 00:07:24.890
And that's great.

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:27.400
There are these fundamental
links between numbers, between

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:29.680
maths, to music.

00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:33.790
And it's great to actually embed
those so tightly as we

00:07:33.790 --> 00:07:35.040
do in this song.

